When #DuaLipa answered rapid-fire questions atop a mechanical bull for W last summer, we did not anticipate the exercise to serve as training for her music video, ‘Love Again,’ in which she stars as a line-dancing, bull-riding cowgirl. To see the progress the pop superstar has made from rookie to rodeo clown, visit the link in our bio. 
-
Director: @shayanasadi
W MAG VIDEO: @_a_b_g, @michael_beckert, @tilden.bissell, @rppr 
Special Thanks to @bigskystudios

@danielkaluuya’s Oscar acceptance speech will go down in history as one of the Academy Awards' most memorable moments. Not only did the actor, who won Best Supporting Actor for his portrayal of Fred Hampton in #JudasandtheBlackMessiah, mortify his mother—“My mom met my dad. They had sex. It’s amazing!”—he also profoundly addressed the push for racial justice. “There’s so much work to do guys,” he told the star-studded crowd. “And that’s on everyone in this room, this ain’t no single man job.” Back in 2018, the London native spoke with W about racism in the UK and the US. Three years later, the work continues.
-
Directed by Lynn Hirschberg
W MAG VIDEO
W magazine Vol. 1 2018, Best Performances

Today’s superstars make their names on @Twitch. The livestreaming platform, which Amazon purchased in 2014, now hosts close to 30 million average daily visitors, up from 17.5 million before the pandemic hit. This boom has resulted in an entire generation of young people who view @tsm_myth, @DrLupo, @Pokimanelol, @loserfruit, @gmhikaru, @alexisayeee_ and @nigelsylvester as mainstream celebrities with the influence and clout typically reserved for professional athletes and pop stars.

node.text:
W has always been—and always will be—a must-read, on screen and off. From Working Girl to Gossip Girl, Kim Kardashian to Marissa Cooper, the magazine has had its fair share of pop culture mentions over the decades. Here, some of the most iconic. Note to Carrie Bradshaw: We’re going to have to side with Berger on this one. We have no issue with scrunchies.
-
Video: @brian__lynch @pier59studios

node.text:
@savannahwelch as Mare Sheehan from ‘Mare of Easttown’ | For W’s second annual TV Portfolio we asked 26 sought-after stars to embody their favorite characters from their favorite comfort shows.

“Her character wasn’t a pretty version of a detective,” Welch, who plays Barbara Gordon on @dctitans says of Kate Winslet’s Mare. “The young mother [Erin], although she had a very small role, she stole the show for me. Even though I was 27 when I had my son, I could relate to that kind of loneliness and the desperation and feeling a bit...I don’t want to say ostracized, but just because of the new reality, friend groups that weren’t really there yet or didn’t have children yet and couldn’t relate to them anymore.”

At the link in bio, the @dctitans star discusses playing the beloved DC Comics character who’s become a symbol of empowerment for both feminists and the disability community.
-
Photography: @toddvwolfsonphoto
Photo Assistant: William McKinney

@chiaraaurelia as Miriam ‘Midge’ Maisel from ‘The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel’ | For W’s second annual TV Portfolio we asked 26 sought-after stars to embody their favorite characters from their favorite comfort shows.

“It was definitely a shock,” the @cruelsummer star says of her hit series’ surprise ending. “I was kind of the sleuth of the cast, always trying to put all the pieces together, see what information I could gather. It took us quite a long time to discover it.”

Read on at the link in our bio.

“I’m not very good at watching TV,” the ‘Warrior’ star says. “Once you get into the industry and you see how things are made, it kind of ruins things. But I got completely immersed in 'Ozark.' “He was of the times in many ways,” the #Euphoria and @feartwd star says of the legendary designer Halston (played by Ewan McGregor in the Ryan Murphy-produced miniseries). “He knew he had talent, but he also was trying to become more commercial. It was like the great argument of art and commerce, and fighting with integrity.”
